\section{The Firm and its Economic Problem}
\textbf{Opportunity cost} of any action is the highest-valued alternative forgone. Opportunity cost includes both explicit costs and implicit costs. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Explicit costs} are paid in money. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Implicit costs} occur when a firm forgoes an alternative action but does not make a payment. For example when a firm uses its own capital, or uses its owner's time or financial resources. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Implicit rental rate of capital} is the cost of using a firms capital, when it could have rented the capital out. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Economic depreciation} is the change in the market value of capital over a given period. It is a implicit cost. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Interest forgone} is the interest lost on the money used to buy capital or that is allocated to some other purpose. It is a implicit cost. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Accounting costs} largely about explicit costs (for example, the cost of machinery, deprecation of value of assets, etc.) \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Economic costs} include implicit costs, as well as in the case of a single proprietorship entrepreneurial skills and capital. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Normal profit} is the return that a entrepreneur sees on his business. It is a opportunity cost as it could have been reinvested in the business. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Economic profit} is \emph{Total Revenue - Total Cost (total cost includes opportunity cost)}. \\
\hfill \\
The objective of economic accounting is to maximize economic profit. To do so a firm must make five basic decisions:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item What goods and services to produce and in what quantities?
  \item How to produce - the techniques of production to use.
  \item How to organize and compensate its managers and workers.
  \item How to market and price its products.
  \item What to produce itself and what to buy from other firms.
\end{enumerate}
\hfill \\
There are three features of a firm's environment that limit the maximum profit that it can make:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Technology
  \item Information
  \item Market
\end{enumerate}


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Technological and Economic Efficiency %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Technological and Economic Efficiency}
\textbf{Technological efficiency} is a process that uses the least inputs for a given output. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Economic efficiency} is a process that uses the least cost for a given output. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Production Efficiency} is a process that is the most technological efficient and economic efficient. \\
\hfill \\


