\section{Information and Organization}
\textbf{Command systems} Hierarchies used for communicate information upwards and barking commands back downwards. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Incentive systems} Configuring payments, benefits, and other incentives to employees in a attempt to maximize the profits of the firm. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{The principal-agent problem} is the problem of devising compensation rules that induce an \emph{agent} to act in the best interest of a \emph{principal}. Three ways of attempting to cope with the principal-agent problem are \textbf{ownership, incentive pay, and long-term contracts}. It is important to note that commands do not work for the principal-agent problem because in most firms the shareholders can effectively monitor the managers and the managers can't effectively monitor the employees. \\
\hfill \\

