\section{Markets and the Competitive Environment}

\hfill \\
\textbf{Perfect competition} is where there are many firms selling \emph{identical} products, many buyers, and no restrictions on the entry of new firms into the industry. Good examples are worldwide markets for corn,rice, and other grain crops. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Monopolistic competition} is where a large number of firms compete by making similar but slightly different products. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Oligopoly} is a market structure in which a small number of firms compete. Good examples are computer software, airplane manufacture, and international air transportation. \\
\hfill \\
\textbf{Monopoly} is where there is only one firm which produces a good or service with no close substitutes and there is a large protective barrier to entry of new firms. For example, the electric utility. \\
\hfill \\
