There are three main limitations of using only concentration measures as determinants of market structure and their failure to take proper account of:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item The geographical scope of the market. Concentration measures take a national view of the market, where sometimes a regional or global view is more accurate.
  \item Barriers to entry and firm turnover. Some industries are highly concentrated but have easy entry and an enormous amount of turnover of firms. For example, a restaurant in a small town. Also, an industry might be competitive because of \emph{potential entry}. For example, there might be only a few firms in a market, but many firms can easily enter the market if economic profits are available.
  \item The correspondence between a market and an industry. The Department of Commerce classifies each firm as being in a particular industry. Markets do not always correspond closely with industries for three reasons:
  \begin{enumerate}
    \item Markets are narrower than industries. For example, the pharmaceutical industry, where there are few firms but many different markets for individual products (drugs). 
    \item Most firms make several products. For example, General Electric.
    \item Firms switch from one market to another based on profit opportunities. For examples, newspapers going online.
  \end{enumerate}
\end{enumerate}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Markets and Firms                %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% 
\section{Markets and Firms}

Markets are good at coordinating decisions. They do so by adjusting prices and making the decisions of buyers and sellers consistent - making the quantity demanded equal to the quantity supplied for each good and service. \\

Firms are often more efficient than markets as coordinators of economic activity because they can achieve:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Lower transaction costs.
  \item Economies of scale.
  \item Economies of scope (use of specialization and often expensive resources to produce a \emph{range of goods and services}.
  \item Economies of team production (individuals in a group specializing in mutually supportive tasks).
\end{itemize}


